02806 Social Data Analysis and Visualization¶

Final Project B - Explainer Notebook¶

1. Motivation¶

The primary aim of the project was to explore the possible relationship between conflict and COVID-19. Social distancing has been a norm in most Western countries for the past months, and most 'non-essential' travel has been forbidden by authorities (or rendered impossible by transportation).

This got the authors thinking whether conflict, armed or otherwise, fell under this category. Is war put on hold out of fear for the virus? Are protests postponed to increase the safety of the masses? These were the questions that sparked this project.

Two data sets were used, one is a conflict dataset covering the Middle-Eastern countries since 2015 (https://acleddata.com/curated-data-files/). It is updated very regularly and has extensive data on most events that occur within the Middle-East that have anything to do with conflict. Secondly, we used the global COVID-19 data provided by John's Hopkins University, fetched upstream (https://datahub.io/core/covid-19). These datasets are high in quality and updated regularly, which was the primary motivators for using them.

We wanted to explore the relationship between the COVID-19 epidemic and conflict within the Middle-East. As it is a Data Visualization course, we of course thought of the best ways to portray this. We want the viewer to both see the scale of the virus and the conflict, this is achieved through overview- and heatmaps, and to gain an idea of whether there's a link between the two. This can be achieved mostly by aligning the data side-by-side or showing graphs. It is a curious subject, and we'd like the reader to take this question with them.

2.2. cont.¶

As can be seen, the countries most affected by conflict events are Syria and Yemen, followed by Iraq, Turkey and Lebanon.

The most common type of event in 2020 is unfortunately Explosions/Remote violence, followed by Protests and Battles.

2.2. cont.¶

As can be seen, Turkey and Iran have the most confirmed cases by far. This poses a stark contrast to surrounding countries such as Jordan, Lebanon and Syria, all of which also have large populations. This is probably due to the fact of insufficient testing in these countries.

This analysis only tells part of the story. 'Confirmed' cases only indicates the total number of confirmed cases since measurements began. To get the current active cases, we have to subtract the number of deceased and the number of recovered. We'll do this by adding another column, "Active", to the dataframe:
